      },
      "output": "\nThe sky appears blue due to a phenomenon called **Rayleigh scattering**. Here's how it works:\n\n1. **Sunlight Composition**: Sunlight appears white but is actually made up of all visible wavelengths (colors) of light, each with different energies and wavelengths.\n\n2. **Scattering in the Atmosphere**: When sunlight enters Earth's atmosphere, it collides with gas molecules (primarily nitrogen and oxygen) and tiny particles. These particles are much smaller than the wavelength of visible light.\n\n3. **Wavelength Dependence**: Shorter wavelengths of light (blue and violet, around 400-500 nanometers) are scattered much more efficiently by these tiny particles than longer wavelengths (red, orange, yellow, around 600-700 nanometers). The scattering intensity is inversely proportional to the fourth power of the wavelength (\u221d 1/\u03bb\u2074), meaning blue light is scattered about 10 times more than red light.\n\n4. **Human Perception**: Although violet light is scattered even more than blue, our eyes are less sensitive to violet, and some of the upper atmosphere absorbs violet light. Additionally, the blue wavelengths dominate what we perceive, making the sky appear blue.\n\n**Why sunrises/sunsets are red/orange**: When the sun is near the horizon, sunlight must pass through a much thicker layer of atmosphere. Most of the shorter blue wavelengths get scattered away before reaching our eyes, leaving the longer red, orange, and yellow wavelengths to dominate the direct sunlight we see.\n\nThis same principle explains why the sky appears black on the Moon (no atmosphere to scatter light) and why Mars has a butterscotch sky (different atmospheric composition and particle sizes).",
